The string has two terminals: 

1. ‘t131’ can be produced by NT5 (rule NT5 → 't131').
2. ‘t72’ can be produced by NT5 (rule NT5 → 't72').

The start symbol S has only two possible binary rules:

• S → NT5 NT3  
• S → NT3 NT3  

Thus at least one of the two positions must be an NT3‑derived terminal.  
Scanning every NT3 → '…' rule shows that NT3 never produces ‘t131’ or ‘t72’.  
Consequently no derivation of S can yield the sequence NT5‑terminal followed by NT5‑terminal, so the grammar cannot generate the string “t131 t72”.

No

The only way S can expand to more than one symbol is through  
S → NT5 NT3.  

• NT3 can produce exactly one terminal symbol (it has only rules of the form NT3 → 'token').  
• NT5 can either  
  – produce a single terminal (NT5 → 'token'), or  
  – produce exactly two symbols NT4 NT3.  
      • NT4 again produces exactly one terminal.  
      • NT3 produces exactly one terminal.

Hence:
– If NT5 uses its single‑terminal rule, S would generate 1 (from NT5) + 1 (from NT3) = 2 tokens.  
– If NT5 uses its NT4 NT3 rule, S would generate 1 (NT4) + 1 (NT3 inside NT5) + 1 (NT3 after S) = 3 tokens.

Therefore any string in the language has length 2 or 3, never more.  
The given string contains 40 tokens, so it cannot be generated by the grammar.
